The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer practically all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Still, we're missing something here - a virtual operator that would make the classics cheaper.
Maybe it won't be long.
The fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have written to Mobil.cz many times.
Finally, it was also confirmed by the CTU, which warned that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, there may be a paradox - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS will be cheaper from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to get into the fight.
Maybe it sounds paradoxical, we have three mobile networks here and penetration is well over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to joke about the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
They are often called by Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has repeatedly stated that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classical operator with his own network probably no longer has a chance (by the way, it would probably be hard to find frequencies already).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
Just the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market brought a significant price reduction, to which also classical operators had to react.
At the same time, before the entry of the stickers such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, voices similar to ours were sounded in the UK.
However, it turned out that a place for such operators is and can be really successful.
We don’t have to go too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
Meanwhile, Mobilking is behind the Penta financial group, which owns U:fona, among other things, in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order for them to function effectively, they need far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry with them relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators are usually profiled as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, but this is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be quite a good move and bet on an unbiased target group.
This operator is focused specifically on men.
“Managers choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could be caught up with us.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic without a chance, say mobile operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look too promising.
Rather, there will be the launch of Mobilking in other countries of our region," Jan Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, a spokesman for Penta's financial group, told Mobil.cz.
In this way, she confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Rather, on the contrary, it tries to do everything in order to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
The GTS Novera Group has long been interested in launching a virtual mobile operator, which would like to take the next step towards becoming a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in providing our customers with not only fixed, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already managed to make progress in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl, a spokesman for the group.
Maybe it's going to lighten up for better times.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator should wait perhaps until the end of the year.
For the time being, however, its emergence is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not think that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, no entity has contacted us with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 press department said in a statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators are also referring to the specificity of the Czech market.
Martin Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1>, press spokesman for T-Mobile, adds in rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not yet recorded any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which it would be possible to build further."
He adds: “In the T-Mobile network, it’s hard to find a virtual operator by the end of the year.
At this point, we should already have a specific agreement on the table to be able to think about it in this short horizon."
Vodafone is paying more attention to meeting its own 3G licensing requirements.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: "By negotiating with potential virtual operators, we are open, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is what we consider to be the most beneficial from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The process of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a decrease in prices and thus also to a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when it comes to operators, they can pull one rope at a time, also testifies to the tatany around the creation of the U:phone.
Perhaps the greatest pressure towards <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was at the time of the creation of the U:phone from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> website.
But now U:fon is suitable as an argument why the virtual operator should not be allowed.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> said: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been further strengthened by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and especially on his services."
However, due to this approach of mobile operators, there is a direct inconsistency of the Czech regulatory authorities.
However, it is not just the attitude of the CTU, which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries - does not have the power to intervene in economic competition.
They belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
But he took his typical attitude to the whole issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has yet been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," said Kristian Chalupa, from the Department of External Relations of the OHS.
It is not surprising that this expression has been formulated by the representatives of the operators.
From an authority that is meant to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses its position on the market, it is more than respectable.
Especially when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: “In a foreign country where virtual operators are commonly active, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services.”
But apparently, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the decline in prices do not belong to the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
In the shocking truth of the whole case, there is up to a dramatic contraction of three mobile operators, which results from their reaction.
The question, if it is really just a coincidence, is offered entirely by itself.
As well as absolutely the same price of gasoline at pumping stations is certainly just a work of chance and a tough competitive battle.
"The Office has not found any evidence of any counter-intelligence in this matter, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their dealings in the market.
The necessary tools to open the mobile market for virtual operators are likely to meet the telecommunications regulator as well," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many contentious points.
Of course, there is an analysis of relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications from the point of view of competition are the only market.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the creation of a virtual operator always requires the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - on his network monopoly.
So in a certain segment it must necessarily be dominant.
However, even if we do not allow this argument, it should be at least a warning to <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators are acting in a similar manner.
Complaints by a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) indicate that they encounter very similar obstacles in dealing with all operators.
Taking responsibility for <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications, by which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS gives away the whole issue of hands.
We have met with him in a number of similar cases.
Unfortunately, to the recently adopted novelties of the telecommunications law, the extension of the powers of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> to the field of economic competition in telecommunications has failed to establish, although a number of experts have promised to improve the situation since then.
The representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS need to know more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
That's what happens when no one looks
At the same time, the operation of some pseudo-virtual operators, some of which exist in Czech mobile networks immediately remains unnoticeable.
They are companies that provide their own price lists of mobile phone services, which are only partially public.
This is usually the case with companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The pricelists of these companies will usually only get to the chosen ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic corporate customer to the operator, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, you will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the trading conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there were any cases you're talking about, it could be a violation of the terms of the contract we're dealing with and it could lead to the termination of cooperation with that company," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> said in a statement.
However, it is quite unlikely that similar action would not be taken against responsible people from mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are able to prevent this from happening.
The activities of these companies have an undeniable advantage and, unlike the actual virtual operators, they do not in any way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out about possible problems: "The law allows similar speculation, however, the services of these companies use only an negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone is not led to their name, so they cannot have it fully as normal customers of mobile operators.”
But that should be at least weird.
In addition, another question is opened for UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes above a similar procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has relatively strong powers to disclose similar activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the operators' explanation that they have no idea of such a thing and their business conditions prohibit it.
When we are not the most expensive
As has already fallen several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable decline in prices for services.
In virtually all countries where virtual operators were created, the classical operators tried more or less to defend their creation.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - too small, possibly too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was at this time that regulatory authorities were involved, which were defending not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Whether by formal measures or by informal pressure, the first virtual operator was created, and the next one was dealt with.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators overwhelm the whole case like a hot potato.
From our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that uncertainty in competences is more than appropriate for them in these cases.
But let us not draw near to the grain.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator will appear with us really soon, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If one of the operators has allowed the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain ineligible to reject (discrimination) other interested parties.
And we must stop calling for a path rather than the rest of Europe.
