Interview - The blood that's sure again
Héma-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly delighted, as Héma-Québec became one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained public confidence, which was seriously shaken after the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is generally known, the state blood reserve administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Board was contaminated with the HIV virus and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994, due to this drama and public outcry, the Canadian government launched a public inquiry, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy, and to formulate recommendations to prevent such a disaster.
While Judge Krever hesitated to deliver the report, a committee was set up in some provinces to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this role was taken up by the Gélinea Committee.
Following the Gélineau and Krevere reports, two suppliers were set up in Canada: Héma-Québec, which was to be administered by Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Company for the supply of all provinces and both territories.
“When Héma-Québec started its activities in 1998, only 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system,” Dr. Décary recalls.
“The situation was overwhelming.
With a systematic effort to increase the safety of blood products and constant work in this area over the following years, we have regained public confidence," he says, adding proudly that by the beginning of 2008, Héma-Québec already had confidence in almost 94% of the Quebec population.
Dr. Décary, however, does not lose sight of the fact that “trust is something very fragile.”
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
"At that time, we witnessed in Europe the occurrence of many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, new variants of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease," says the woman, who has led the company since its inception in 1998.
"And we had no idea if this disease could spread blood.
We therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Kreverov and Gélineau report, according to which, in the event that we do not know and when there is a serious disease at the bet of spreading, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterized by the degeneration of the brain, does not cause death.
In April 1999, we therefore turned down blood from people who have been staying in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that this disease is transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that it made sense to stick to the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting the HIV virus appeared on the market: tests using nucleic acid (NAT) that allow the donor blood to detect the presence of the virus itself, and not the presence of antibodies on which the pre-existing tests were based.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the deaf period that occurs between the moment of infection of the patient and the moment when the first virus can be detected in our blood techniques, explains the specialist.
We have been able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors could be infected without them knowing about it and without us being able to figure it out.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
One in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
In other words, it means that before someone gets infected with HIV, 12 million blood products will need to be distributed.
Because Héma-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products annually, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission to appear through the blood product.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe blood transfusions that are necessary for healing,” said Héma-Québek, head of the department.
“The challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
We never know what disease-causing element can occur in the system.
Just last year, a chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by insect bites.
It is necessary to be constantly cautious," continues Dr. Décary, stressing that, in addition to the safe supply, Héma-Québec must also consider the supply sufficient.
“Requirements are growing because the population is ageing.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which on average is made up of only 3% of Quebecers eligible to donate."
Every healthy person is at least 18 years old, meeting the eligibility criteria, but can donate blood only once in 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer blood are not accepted because they are, for example, carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where they order septic tanks, they are excluded for a period of one year.
“With these 3%, we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Disadvantages are very rare.
However, the members of the donor network need to be complemented in proportion to how old they are and can no longer donate blood.
However, convincing people to give blood is difficult, especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so unconnected today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart palpitations, eye bulbs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank in Quebec’s umbilical cord.
The umbilical cord, previously considered a biomedical waste, sheds blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our 1,000 blood sample from the umbilical cord to the bank, and we expect to collect over 1,000 a year.
At the beginning of next year we should start offering them for transplants," explains Dr. Décary, who describes the blood collection program from the umbilical cord as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they don't have access to it," Héma-Québec doesn't have enough resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
