At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate the goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known—and seemingly irrational—behavior have been able to reveal to researchers in the field of neurology and economics at the University of New York.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people don’t want to lag behind in an eBay auction competition, so they’d rather pay too high a price.
Research using an experimental auction tried to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group took part in the auctions, and using the method of functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) were examined the active areas of the brain of the subjects.
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but during the auction game, the important element of which is to overwhelm the other side, began to function intensively during the loss of a whole located under the cerebral cortex, called striatum.
In addition to many other functions, this area of the brain plays a role in the “self-replacement” mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, it is possible, according to the researchers, to explain the effort to avoid a sharp striatum reaction.
To support their theory, members of the research team from a number of economists conducted a financial cross-sectional survey.
Under different conditions, three groups were bidding against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
In addition, the members of the other group were promised that if they exit the game victoriously, they will receive an additional $15 for the reward.
The third group, on the other hand, received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also lost this money.
The difference between the two groups, therefore, consisted of everything in the fact that one was emphasized victory and the other was a loss.
However, the members of the group playing "against loss" were willing to go higher than it was in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
