Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are treated. The reason is that the patient often does not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the generic name for the infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms there are many similarities, it is characteristic of inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the causes of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways depending on the underlying disease: hepatitis A and E by digestive systems (e.g. food infected, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other blood and body fluids (sperm, sweat).
In any case, travellers should be protected against A and B virus vaccination, there is no type C virus vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after eating an infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, and the urge to vomit.
Then yellowing of the skin and whites of the eyes, a light stool and dark urine will be formed. The treatment can take two to three weeks.
Every year, millions of people worldwide die of a more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only one in ten people infected with the drug are treated.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, the cause of the disease destroys the liver cells in a way that causes the first symptoms in many cases up to 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent premature, to carry out regular screening.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more frequently than on average: among people who had undergone blood transfusions before 1991, among drug users and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated worldwide number of individuals infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease may prove to be a routine laboratory examination, a person should, in the event that he or she records any signs of unknown origin, contact his or her practical doctor.
With timely detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, thus preventing infections and preventing the formation of cancer.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, which was organized for the first time worldwide by disease-representing organizations in 2004.
Its aim is to draw attention to the chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of its occurrence and the importance of timely recognition of the disease.
