Intelligent car mimics the plane of a butterfly
What, then, would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not the imitation of obstacles detectors occurring in the world of nature?
Take bees, for example.
The initial strategic idea of a surprise project, presented at the Japanese CEATEC fair, was inspired by engineers from Nissan, and how to build a new generation of collision-preventing systems.
In collaboration with Tokyo University, Nissan has built a biomimetic robotic control system BR23C, a robotic mini-car that is equipped with bee features, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all crashes.
“During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety protective packaging,” explained Kazuhiro Doi, General Manager of the Technology PR and Research and Development brand at the exhibition.
An important role is played by complex eyes, which allow bees to see in all directions at a visual angle of more than 300 degrees.
In order to copy the function of the compound eye, the engineers followed the idea of a laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles at a distance of up to 2 meters before the BR23C in the 180 degree field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns into an operation aimed at preventing a collision.
The obstacle is caught during a split second, then the robotized car begins to mimic the movements of the bees and by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent a collision immediately changes direction.
In contrast to any existing system, this evasive maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If that were not the case, the robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshijuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology suits the most vulnerable and inner layer of the security protection package, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what bees do to avoid other bees.
This process should not take longer than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or downwards, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be rotated.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when avoiding, in the case of a robotic car, only the possibility of rotational movement, acceleration and slowing was applied.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion variants.
According to Andoa, it is important to have an instinctive, intelligent reaction, not the ability to process, but rather the storage of data.
This mechanism must process and respond only to a few incoming signals per second.
It is not necessary to store and react to them using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it constantly uses only memory the size of a few kilobytes.
It does not need memory with gigabyte or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step in the development of a technology that is used to avoid the immediate impact that Nissan is expected to have on mass-produced cars within ten years.
Another possibility of application may be the connection of the unit to the satellite navigation system GPS, which, after avoiding obstacles in the way, would lead the motorist to the specified final destination.
